<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18590509-541">
               <interp inst="t18590509-541" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18590509"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18590509-541" type="date" value="18590509"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18590509-541-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-541-18590509 t18590509-541-offence-1 t18590509-541-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>541. <persName id="def1-541-18590509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18590509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18590509" type="age" value="30"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18590509" type="surname" value="HOGAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-541-18590509" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM HOGAN</hi> (30)</persName>, was indicted<rs id="t18590509-541-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18590509-541-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18590509-541-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="perjury"></interp> for wilful and corrupt perjury.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18590509-name-591" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-591" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-591" type="surname" value="RANSOM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-591" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM RANSOM</persName>
                  </hi>. I am managing assistant clerk at the Southwark County Court—Mr. Whitmore is the Judge—I produce a copy of the entries</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185905090183"></xptr>
               <p>in the plaint book in a case of Parkes <hi rend="italic">v.</hi> Hogan, under the seal of the Court t—the amount claimed is 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—a summons was issued, and the plaintiff and defendant appeared on 15th April—the plaintiff and his brother were examined—they produced this document, and I placed it in the prisoner's hand—he was sworn, and I asked him if his name was William Hogan; he said "Yes"—I said, "Look at that document, is that your writing; he said "I did not write that"—the prosecutor or his brother said "I saw him write it"—I said, "Never mind the body, look at the signature, "William Hogan," and say whether that is your writing?" he positively swore that it was not; I think his words were, "It is not my signature" (the documents are handed up to me, and I put the questions for the Judge)—I said, look at it again," and say whether it is your writing, and he most positively said "No"—I handed the I. O. U. up to the Judge; he looked at the signature, and re<lb></lb>quested me again to hand it to the prisoner; and again the Judge asked "Is that your signature?" and he said "No"—the Judge asked him whether he could write, he said "Yes"—the Judge requested me to give him a pen and ink; I did so, and said "Now write your name;" that paper has been mislaid, and I cannot find it; but he wrote "William" or "Wiltam;" how-ever, the Christian name was spelt wrong—I handed it up to the Judge, who said, "Can you spell your name?"—he said, "Yes;" and spelt "William" correctly—the Judge then cautioned him, and asked him again whether it was his signature—he said, "No"—on that the prosecutor and his brother were examined again, and they swore positively that they saw him sign it and an order was made that he should be committed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BEST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is it part of your duty to examine the cases instead of the Judge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not instead of the Judge; but I do put the question!, by his permission, to facilitate business—I have not got the original copy; the prisoner has that—he appeared as sober as he does now, when he was examined; but in the after part of the day he was excited when I insisted on his putting certain papers in his pocket—the Judge ad<lb></lb>dressed him before his committal to prison—he kept perpetually denying his signature—he said "I owe the money," and commenced pulling a quan<lb></lb>tity of papers out of his pocket—I said "Do not excite yourself; calmly look at that piece of paper, and tell the Judge whether the signature, 'W. Hogan,' is your writing;" and he said "No; it is not;" he stuck to the "No" all through—a man that was not sober might think he could deceive by signing his name wrong; I think so now.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was the interval before the first committal? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> When the Judge ordered him to be committed, it was half-past 1, and I think, before he was sent to prison, it was about 3 in the afternoon.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18590509-name-592" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-592" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-592" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-592" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN JONES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Usher at the Country-court—I administered the oath to the prisoner—I saw him during the whole time he was in Court; I saw nothing like intoxication about him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Have you never cases of drunken people at your Court? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; and we put them on one side till they are sober—drunken persons are not always excited.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18590509-name-593" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-593" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-593" type="surname" value="PARKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-593" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT PARKE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 3, Apollo-buildings, East-street, Walworth. I have a loan office there—the defendant came to my brother, in April, last year, to borrow a Bum of money—I was present—he wanted to borrow a larger sum, but my brother would not lend him more than 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he wrote an I. O. U. for it; and I saw prisoner sign it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18590509-name-594" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-594" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-594" type="surname" value="PARKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-594" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM PARKE</persName>
                  </hi>. I saw the prisoner sign this paper—I was present at the Country-court—he volunteered to give evidence in his own behalf—he admitted the debt, but denied this being his writing.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185905090184"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">WM. RANSOM</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Just explain how that was? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The previous witness is labouring under a mistake; because, if the prisoner had said "I admit the debt;" I should have said "How do you propose to pay it?"—he admitted it in the afternoon—he was put into the box, and immediately sworn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BEST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where was Mr. Parke standing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Near the witness-box—he was not nearer the defendant than me—I should say he could hear as well as me; but he is labouring under a mistake.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witnesses for the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18590509-name-595" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-595" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-595" type="surname" value="BROWNING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-595" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BROWNING</persName>
                  </hi>. I know the prisoner—I saw him on 15th April, the County Court day, in Southwark—I saw him as to making me some clothes—he measured me as far as he could—he was not capable of measur<lb></lb>ing; he was intoxicated—I should consider he was drunk—he had been drinking for a week—he could not measure me as he ought—I should think that was about 10 o'clock in the morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where did you see him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At the "Earl Grey"—I was not in the County Court—I am certain it was on 15th April—I know it, because it is my pension day—I received it the same day—I receive a pension from the police—I go to Scotland-yard for it—I went about 2 o'clock—I happened to go to my brother the same day, and on my way, close to the house, I was given to understand he was in custody; and that was the same morning that he measured me—he tried to measure me—I do not consider he did the thing that was right, and therefore I sent for my cloth and took it back again—that was the same evening—I heard he was in trouble, and I thought I would get him off as far as I could—I went to the County Court and offered bail for him—he is not a relation of mine—I have known him for two years and a half—I have met him at my brother's very often—I never stopped late—I have met him in the morning as well as the evening.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BEST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you seen him since he was taken into custody? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have, in Horsemonger-lane gaol—he has been in gaol the whole time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18590509-name-596" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-596" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-596" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18590509-name-596" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I am a tinman, and reside in Oakley-street, Lam<lb></lb>beth—I know the prisoner—I saw him on 15th April—I cannot exactly say what time, but somewhere about 10 or 11 o'clock—he was then in liquor—I had seen him the day before—he was in liquor then—he was not excited, but quietly drunk.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long were you with him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Perhaps five or ten minutes—we were talking—I met him in the street on the day before; at the time I am speaking of, it was in the Earl Grey—I heard of this the day he was locked up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say he was quiet; could he walk? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I know he was in liquor, because he spoke in that way—when a man is in liquor, he cannot speak so plain as when sober—I knew he had been drinking for two or three days previously—I was talking to him about going to work—he said he was going on the following day—I believe he understood what I said—this was on the day previous, when I spoke to him about going to work; not the morning he was locked up—I was talking to him about ten minutes on the same morning he was locked up—I was not talking to him then about going to work—I dare say he understood what I said—I know he was in liquor very much.</p>
               <p>
